Intro

I have experience of programming in Python, Fortran, C, and Matlab and scripting in several languages, however, I have not used R that much. Also, my conding skills have been diminished in my time doing medicine. The syntax seems familiar in some ways. The RStudio looks useful and the Git integration is a nice modern way of version control. I would like to learn to use more R than SPSS and Stata as the latter are proprietary software and R is much more versatile. I found the course from the pool of courses suitable for doctoral studies. As I am missing 5 ECTS and the course is just that, I thought that this would be useful and fun.

As I mentioned, the syntax has some similarities, especially with Matlab and perhaps LaTeX as well. It is always somewhat an effort to move from one language to another and try to remember the small things. Fortunately the bigger picture is quite the same as computers work as the way they do.

According to this linear model gender and age were not statistically significant, but Attitude was p<0.001 (Pr 8.34e-09). Multiple R-squared (model fit) was 0.2018.

New try with just Attitude as the only explanatory variable

fit_points2 <- data_read_2014 %>% lm(Points ~ Attitude, data = .)

# Model parameters, model performance
summary(fit_points2)

## F-statistic: 38.61 on 1 and 164 DF,  p-value: 4.119e-09

This yields a slightly lower (0.1906) Multiple R-squared, but the difference is small. This suggests that other than Attitude does not have much effect on the model performance.

Residuals mean the difference between the model prediction and the actual values of Points.

Estimates are the coefficients for the linear model.

The first linear model here is in the following form Points = Intercept (Estimate) + Age* (Estimate) + Attitude* (Estimate) + gender* (Estimate)

The second linear model here is in the following form Points = Intercept (Estimate) + Attitude* (Estimate)

Standard Error is the standard error of the estimate. The standard error can be used to calculate the confidence intervals, e.g., 95% if the data is normally distributed and model assumptions hold, e.g., modeled value and the explanatory variable have indeed linear relationship.

t value is Estimate divided by Standard error.

Pr(>|t|) is the p-value for the individual coefficients. If the probability is low enough (arbitrary, usually p<0.05 or p<0.01) we can reject the null hypothesis. In this case, the null hypothesis is that the coefficient (Estimate) is 0.

Multiple R-squared is a measure of how well the model fits into the data (what proportion of the variance is explained by the model).

The Estimate of Attitude in the linear model above is 3.5255. This would mean that the higher the value of Attitude, higher the Points. The Attitude means a numeral value of global attitude toward statistics. My interpretation of this is that students who score higher in the questions concerning attitudes towards statistics will eventually learn the subject better and score higher in the test (higher Points).

In both models the Multiple R-squared values are close to each other (0.2018 vs.Â 0.1906). The bit higher goodness of fit in the first model with three explanatory variables is probably explained mainly by the Age that although not statistically significant (p = 0.159) does have some influence. When compared model with Age+Attitude vs.Â Attitude+Gender (not in the code), the former fits better.

Larger plot to check Cookâs distance

(Age + Attitude + Gender vs.Â Points)

# Larger plot to check Cook's distance
# (Age + Attitude + Gender vs. Points)
plot(fit_points,5)

(Attitude vs.Â Points)

# (Attitude vs. Points)
plot(fit_points2,5)

Residuals vs.Â fitted This plot is used to show if the residuals have non-linear patterns. As the model here is a linear model non-linear patterns would be a message that the type of model used here is a wrong one. There should be equal spread of points on the both sides of the horizontal line. No clear non-linear pattern is seen in models 1 and 2.

Normal Q-Q Observations should be normally distributed around fitted line seen in these plots. Here the residuals diverge from the straight line in the left and in the right side of the plot. I think the plot look reasonable good in both cases.

Residuals vs.Â Leverage The plot helps for finding outliers that can influence the model and model fit quite a lot. The model fit might improve if these outliers were excluded. Sure it is good to question what the excluded values are and it is appropriate to exclude them. The possible outliers should reside outside Cookâs distance. As seen in the plots (and additional plots) the Cookâs distance is outside the plotted field. I believe it is safe to say that the data used here have no influential outliers.

Data is about alcohol consumption of students in secondary education of two Portuguese schools.

Data does have a matrix 370 (entries = persons) x 35 (columns = variables). Variables are both character variables and real numbers (double). There is one logical variable (high_use), however, several others are binary (or logical or categorical) variables but they have just imported as real numbers. There are no missing values.

Alcohol consumption (alc_use) ranges from \(1.0\) to \(5.0\), mean \(1.9\) with sd \(1.0\) and median \(1.5\).

Data description from https://archive.ics.uci.edu/dataset/320/student+performance

3 Variables and some plots

The four variables chosen to study with high/low alcohol comsumption (variable high_use thatâs alc_use > 2): 7 Medu, 14 studytime, 21 higher, and 24 famrel.

  • 7 Medu = motherâs education (numeric: 0 - none, 1 - primary education (4th grade), 2 - 5th to 9th grade, 3 - secondary education or 4 - higher education). Hypothesis: Motherâs education has had influence on childâs education, I reckon that higher education will decrease the alcohol consumption

  • 14 studytime = weekly study time (numeric: 1 - <2 hours, 2 - 2 to 5 hours, 3 - 5 to 10 hours, or 4 - >10 hours) Hypothesis: Higher the studytime per week lower the alcohol consumption (no time to drink)

  • 21 higher = wants to take higher education (binary: yes or no) Hypothesis: If student wants to have higher education, probably they would be more inclined to study and not to drink that much. Motherâs education might be a confounding factor here.

  • 24 famrel = quality of family relationships (numeric: from 1 - very bad to 5 - excellent) Hypothesis: Better the relationships with family, less alcohol consumption.

Analysis of odds ratios

In univariable model the higher educational aspirations have p=0.019, however, when put into the multivariable model there is no statistical significant effect anymore. Probably due to low numbers of students how admitted low educational aspirations. Otherwise, the only statistically significant univariable model parameters were studytime 3 and 4.

It looks that the study time variable is the only one with statistically significant effect on the low or high alcohol consumption. Here the groups 3 and 4 have negative odds rations, and the absolute values, which are \(0.26\) and \(0.25\) in multivariable model, are less than \(1\). This suggests that the students who spend more time studying have lower odds for using high amounts of alcohol than the ones studying only \(<2\) hours per week.

Model R-square is just \(0.1\) and adjusted R-square \(0.075\). It seems that the model ainât that good.

# Calculate predictions using the general linear model
alc_high_pred <- predict(high_use_mod)

# Some data modifications that the data and the modeled data can be compared (different data types double vs. lgl)
glm_probs <- data.frame(probs = predict(high_use_mod, type="response"))
head(glm_probs)
##       probs
## 1 0.2913594
## 2 0.2492977
## 3 0.3247049
## 4 0.1776290
## 5 0.4078263
## 6 0.2211599
# All data that has probability >0.5 will be classified as TRUE, other FALSE

glm_pred <- glm_probs %>% mutate(pred = ifelse(probs>.5, "TRUE", "FALSE"))

glm_pred$pred_lgl <- as.logical(glm_pred$pred)
glm_pred <- cbind(data_alc, glm_pred)

2x2 cross-tabulation predicted vs.Â data

# 2x2 cross-tabulation positives vs. negatives, confusion matrix
# Predictions as columns, data (real values) as rows
# Fill 0 might be problematic (missing values noted as 0 => false), however, here we have no missing values.
glm_pred %>% count(pred_lgl, high_use) %>% spread(high_use, n, fill = 0)
##   pred_lgl FALSE TRUE
## 1    FALSE   244   89
## 2     TRUE    15   22

2x2 cross-tabulation (or rather the general linear model) gives us as true positives (sensitivity) \(\frac{22}{89+22}=0.198\), false positives \(\frac{89}{22+89}=0.802\), true negatives (specificity) \(\frac{244}{244+15}=0.942\), and false negatives \(\frac{15}{244+15}=0.0579\) in cases. Model gave correct value in \(244+22=266\) times out of \(370\) succeeding in \(\frac{266}{370}=0.719\) cases. Thus, the training error is \(1-0.719 = 0.281 = 28.1\%\). Please note that here the training data and the validation data for the model is the same. Even though this is the case, a perfect model construction is not possible with this approach as the training error shows. Quite probably the test error (using the model for actual predictions for new data) would be larger.

The models sensitivity is certainly low \(0.198\) that means that it is not good finding the cases where alcohol consumption is high. Specificity is better \(0.942\) that means that the students with low use of alcohol will not be classified wrong as easily. I would not use this model for finding the high alcohol consumption students.
